#week-title("Two", "The Ethics of Transmission")

=== Core Teaching

The ethics of transmission in the alchemical tradition are ancient, clear, and
directly applicable to the Adept who now has something genuinely worth sharing.

*Share only with those who have demonstrated sincere preparation.* This is not
elitism — it is care. A preparation given to someone unprepared for it does
not elevate them; it confuses them or, in the worst cases, gives them material
for ego-inflation rather than genuine development. The tradition's reticence
about sharing with the unprepared is not about guarding secrets — the texts
are publicly available. It is about the recognition that understanding requires
preparation, and preparation takes time.

*Do not boast.* The practitioner who advertises the results of their Work, who
seeks recognition from those outside the tradition, who uses the work as social
capital — this practitioner has violated the Oath's first requirement (silence)
and has introduced an impurity into the Work that will compromise subsequent
preparations. This is not merely an ethical failing; the tradition regards it
as a practical disqualifier.

*Do not diminish the Work by sensationalising it.* The popular image of
alchemy — dramatic transformations, gold from lead, miraculous cures — is
precisely what the sincere practitioner must not reproduce. The Work is
genuinely remarkable, but its remarkableness is subtle, cumulative, and visible
only to those who have been present with it across time. Claiming more than is
demonstrable both dishonours the tradition and misleads potential practitioners.

*Honour the lineage by working honestly and humbly within it.* This means: cite
sources correctly. Acknowledge what you do not know. Do not claim to have
produced results that you have not produced. Do not present received knowledge
as personal discovery. The tradition's texts are available; there is no virtue
in concealing their source.

*The difference between teacher and guide.* The Adept who has completed three
years is not qualified to teach in the sense of setting curriculum, evaluating
students, or providing clinical support for inner work crises. They are
qualified to guide: to accompany a practitioner at an earlier stage, to share
what they have observed, to help the earlier practitioner avoid errors they
themselves made, and to witness the earlier practitioner's work with honest
attention.

